le of Declaration of Independence signatory John Hancock (1736/7–93), was among the foremost of 18th-century American businessmen. He was a descendant of Nathaniel Hancock, who was known to have been in Cambridge, MA, as early as 1634. Born in Braintree, MA, John Hancock was president of the Second Continental Congress and the first governor of the state of MA."],"variants":[{"name":"Hancox","meanings":["English: variant of   Hancock  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Handcock","meanings":["English: variant of   Hancock   with intrusive <i>-d-</i>."]},{"name":"Hann","meanings":["German and Dutch: from a shortened pet form of the personal name <i>Johann</i> (see   John  ).","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Hann</i>, commonly a pet form of <i>Henry</i> (Middle English <i>Hanry</i>). <i>Hann</i> could also be a rhyming pet form of Randolph (Middle English <i>Randal</i>, shortened to <i>Ran</i> or <i>Rand</i>). <i>Han</i> was also a pet form of <i>Joh(a)n</i> in Middle Dutch, and it is possible that this usage was brought to England by Flemings after the Norman Conquest, but no evidence has yet been found that it was similarly used in Middle English. See   Henry   and   Randall  , and compare   Hankin  ,   Hancock  , and   Hanks  .","English: variant of   Ann   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William Hancock had at least 2 sons with William Hancok."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","about 1330":"umbes 1330","about 1340":"umbes 1340","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","about 1330":"noin 1330","about 1340":"noin 1340","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1310–Male":"1310–Décédé","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","about 1330":"environ 1330","about 1340":"environ 1340","England":"Angleterre","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs William Hancock a eu au moins 2 fils avec William Hancok."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1310–Male":"1310–Verstorben","1330–Male":"1330–Verstorben","1340–Male":"1340–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","about 1330":"um 1330","about 1340":"um 1340","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Mrs William Hancock hatte mit William Hancok mindestens 2 Söhne."},"ht":{"–":"Desede","1310–Male":"1310–Desede","1330–Male":"1330–Desede","1340–Male":"1340–Desede","–Female":"Desede","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","about 1330":"about 1330","about 1340":"about 1340","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Angletè, United Kingdom"},"hu":{"–":"elhunyt","1310–Male":"1310–elhunyt","1330–Male":"1330–elhunyt","1340–Male":"1340–elhunyt","–Female":"elhunyt","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","about 1330"